The OpenAI Critique
-------------------

I wrote in yesterday's conclusion:

That leaves America, and a choice we have to make. We could, for very logic=
al reasons, double down on defensive measures, like massively expanding the=
 chip ban and imposing a permission-based regulatory regime on chips and se=
miconductor equipment that mirrors the E.U.=E2=80=99s approach to tech; alt=
ernatively, we could realize that we have real competition, and actually gi=
ve ourself permission to compete. Stop wringing our hands, stop campaigning=
 for regulations =E2=80=94 indeed, go the other way, and cut out all of the=
 cruft in our companies that has nothing to do with winning. If we choose t=
o compete we can still win, and, if we do, we will have a Chinese company t=
o thank.

Some folks read this as being simply about government regulations =E2=80=94=
