I think that Jobs had cause-and-effect backwards: there are not 30,000 manu=
facturing engineers in the U.S. because there are not 30,000 manufacturing =
engineering jobs to be filled. That is because the structure of the world e=
conomy =E2=80=94 choices made starting with Bretton Woods in particular, an=
d cemented by the removal of tariffs over time =E2=80=94 made them nonviabl=
e. Say what you will about the viability or wisdom of Trump=E2=80=99s tarif=
fs, the motivation =E2=80=94 to undo eighty years of structural changes =E2=
=80=94 is pretty straightforward!

The other thing about Jobs=E2=80=99 answer is how ultimately self-serving i=
t was. This is not to say it was wrong: Apple could not only not manufactur=
e an iPhone in the U.S. because of cost, it also can=E2=80=99t do so becaus=
e of capability; that capability is downstream of an ecosystem that has dev=
eloped in Asia and a long learning curve that China has traveled and that t=
he U.S. has abandoned. Ultimately, though, the benefit to Apple has been pr=
ofound: the company has the best supply chain in the world, centered in Chi=
na, that gives it the capability to build computers on an unimaginable scal=
e with maximum quality for not that much money at all.

Connect this to Google: what if Google had taken @roon's advice, and not wa=
sted the time of valuable "researchers" in transforming how data centers ar=
e built? Perhaps they could have waited until Alibaba did it a decade later=
, and rented capacity? And, in the meantime, they would have been a far sma=
ller and less significant company specifically, and the entire U.S. tech in=
dustry would be similarly stunted generally.

To be fair to @roon, he does seem to be talking narrowly about the specific=
 optimizations that DeepSeek made to overcome the H800's nerfed memory band=
width, but I think the critique holds more generally: U.S. tech companies, =
including OpenAI, have clearly in retrospect been Nvidia's willing suckers,=
 happy to pay for more capacity instead of wringing out their own; how many=
 years would it have taken them to discover DeepSeek's breakthroughs indepe=
ndently? No, infrastructure optimization isn't sexy, but it matters.

Indeed, I'd go further: every person in AI is echoing Satya Nadella's invoc=
ation of Jevons paradox ( https://twitter.com/satyanadella/status/188375389=
9255046301 ) , i.e. the idea that cheaper computing drives more usage, but =
the reason you know that is cope =E2=80=94 even if it's true! =E2=80=94 is =
because the revealed preference of every tech company was that they saw mor=
e value in one more researcher than in one more infrastructure engineer. Wh=
ich again, is why every single person who actually believes in AI and Jevon=
s paradox should be sending thank you notes to DeepSeek.

Aggregation Theory and Cheap AI
-------------------------------

Back in January Doug O'Laughlin wrote his 2025 AI & Semiconductor Outlook (=
 https://www.fabricatedknowledge.com/p/2025-ai-and-semiconductor-outlook ) =
on Fabricated Knowledge:

I will admit. After two incredible years of the AI trade, I was worried tha=
t it would become long in the tooth at the end of the year. Ironically, one=
 of the most bullish things possible happened at the end of the year: O3. W=
hile the world was focused on scaling laws, there are still many dimensions=
 of improvement ahead of us, and O3 gave us a taste of the future.

I believe that there is no practical limit to the improvements of models ot=
her than economics, and I think that will be the real constraint in the fut=
ure. It is reasonable that if we spent infinite dollars on a model, it woul=
d be improved. The problem is whether infinite dollars would make sense for=
 a business. That is going to be the key question for 2025. How do the econ=
omics of AI make this work? One of the core assumptions about the internet =
has just been broken. Marginal costs now exist again, meaning that most hyp=
erscalers will become increasingly capital-intensive.

The era of aggregation theory is behind us, and AI is again making technolo=
gy expensive. This relation of increased cost from increased consumption is=
 anti-internet era thinking. And this will be the big problem that will be =
reckoned with this year. Hyperscaler=E2=80=99s business models are mainly u=
nderpinned by the marginal cost being zero. So, as long as you set up the i=
nfrastructure and fill an internet-scale product with users, you can make m=
oney.

This era will soon be over, and the future will be much weirder and more co=
mpute-intensive. Looking back on the 2010s, we will probably consider them =
a naive time in the long arc of technology. One of our fundamental assumpti=
ons about this period is unraveling. This will be the single most significa=
nt change in the technology landscape going forward.

